    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1953-04-05T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1953-04-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="641"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d641">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">794.00/4–553</note>
                <head>No. 641<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan (<persName corresp="#p_MRD1"
                            type="from">Murphy</persName>) to the Director of the Office of
                        Northeast Asian Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_YKT1" type="to"
                            >Young</persName>)</hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d641fn1">A date stamp indicates that this letter was
                        received in the Office of Northeast Asian Affairs on Apr. 10.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1953-04-05">April 5,
                            1953</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Dear <persName corresp="#p_YKT1">Ken</persName>
                    </hi>: I lunched with Mr. <persName corresp="#p_YS1">Yoshida</persName> on April
                    2 at his house in Oiso and after lunch he handed me a confidential <hi
                        rend="italic">aide-mémoire</hi> of which a copy is enclosed.</p>
                <p>On March 24 he also wrote me a penned note, a copy of which is enclosed.<note
                        n="2" xml:id="d641fn2">Neither enclosure is printed.</note>
                </p>
                <p>The three items which he mentions in these communications are very much on his
                    mind, viz., (1) a World Bank loan for power development; (2) Japanese
                    administration of Amami Oshima; and (3) release and/or reduction of terms of
                    Japanese war criminals.</p>
                <p>I don’t know what, if anything, the Department can do about any of these, and I
                    gave Mr. <persName corresp="#p_YS1">Yoshida</persName> no assurance that
                    anything could be done while at the same time expressing sympathy in these
                    issues which are of obvious importance in the electoral campaign.<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d641fn3">Elections for the House of Representatives were to be held
                        on Apr. 19.</note> I promised to pass them on to you for whatever
                    consideration might be possible. Mr. <persName corresp="#p_YS1"
                        >Yoshida</persName> reiterated several times, as has Mr. <persName
                        corresp="#p_OK1">Okazaki</persName>, that if some reassuring public
                    statement could be vouchsafed by the United States on these subjects, it would
                    be of great value to him.</p>
                <p>All the best to you.</p>
                <p>Yours sincerely,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bob</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
